  "enhanced_information": "Aspirin is contraindicated in peptic ulcer due to its potential to cause gastrointestinal irritation and increase the risk of bleeding, which can complicate existing ulcers. This is supported by the consensus that aspirin can exacerbate peptic ulcer disease. In contrast, aspirin is not contraindicated in myalgia, as it is often used to reduce inflammation associated with muscle pain. While aspirin can cause Reye's syndrome in children, leading to a contraindication in fever in pediatric patients, this is not a general contraindication for fever in adults. Aspirin is beneficial in unstable angina as it provides cardiovascular protection, thus it is not contraindicated in this condition."
